民族音樂學研究概念與採譜方法論：以其於臺灣原住民音樂研究之應用為例 















							    









民族音樂學研究概念與採譜方法論：以其於臺灣原住民音樂研究之應用為例 


熱門：204











資料識別：
ioe:pub:6654 .
資料類型：
書目文獻 
主題與關鍵字：
相關族群:賽夏族 相關族群:阿美族 關鍵字:音樂 
描述：
摘要:對於臺灣原住民音樂，早期利用歐洲比較音樂學的研究方法，註重探討音樂結構，音組織、旋律、節奏等音樂要素；直至1980年代開始，受美洲民族音樂學思潮影響，漸將音樂視為人類的產物，並以人為音樂研究的中心議題，試圖融合人類學、民族學、社會學、語言學等相關學科理論於音樂研究中。但由於音樂研究本身的技術性與專業性，致使參與臺灣原住民音樂研究的學者並不多，連帶對於原住民各個部落音樂聲響的採記，仍多利用一次採錄的描述性記譜法概念。描述性記譜法雖屬客觀，但其以田野調查中一次性的音樂錄音為記寫樂譜時的唯一依據，則可能產生有些採譜者，對於所採記音樂的認識，在概念上有根本性的錯誤之虞，因而使得其所採記的樂譜信度降低。至於本研究中對於阿美族有意識的應用超越十二平均律以外的音高概念，以及賽夏族特殊樂曲曲式結構的發現，則是研究者對於不同時間、地點下相同音樂段落，利用概念性採譜的具體成果。因此對於概念性採譜方法的應用，則可重新詮釋原住民的音樂聲響。 (本文摘要) Abstract:In the study of Taiwanese            aboriginal music at an earlier time, the European            comparative musicological method, noted for the            investigation in musical elements like music structure,            Tonsystem, melody, rhythm, etc., was widely applied. Since            1980s, under the influence of American ethnomusico-logical            concepts, researchers of Taiwanese aboriginal music started            to see music as a human behavior, and conducted their            projects in the theme of "human." They tried to do            their music research with touches of anthropology,            ethnology, sociology, and linguistics.The traditional            descriptive notation was adopted to transcribe tlie tribal            music. The descriptive notation, although objective, trusts            the one-time musical recording as the only evidence for            transcription; there are possibilities that conceptual            errors could lie made due to the insufficient understanding            of the music taken, which consequently reduces the            reliability of the notation.The findings of this research —            the conscious use of pitches exceeding the equal temperament            by the Amis tribe and the special musical form and structure            of the Saisiat tribe, are concrete consequences resulted            from the new conceptual transcription method the researcher            practiced at different times and locations to the same            pieces of music. The application of this method will provide            a new view to interpret the acoustical embodiment of the            aboriginal music of Taiwan. (本文摘要) 
